<item>
            <title>[KAFKA-4247] kafka-run-class has potential to add a leading colon to classpath</title>
                <link>https://issues.apache.org/jira/browse/KAFKA-4247</link>
                <project id="12311720" key="KAFKA">Kafka</project>
                    <description>&lt;p&gt;&lt;a href=&quot;https://github.com/confluentinc/kafka/blob/trunk/bin/kafka-run-class.sh#L128-L133&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;https://github.com/confluentinc/kafka/blob/trunk/bin/kafka-run-class.sh#L128-L133&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;In the event CLASSPATH has not yet been populated this will result in &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;:$file &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Normally this wouldn&apos;t be a problem however Connect&apos;s AbstractClassHearder uses ClasspathHelper.forJavaClassPath() to collect it&apos;s eligible classes. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;With a leading colon you will endup with a entry for null which is expanded to the working directory. &lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;java -cp &quot;:&quot; test&lt;br/&gt;
[]&lt;/p&gt;


&lt;p&gt;java -cp &quot;:Users&quot; test&lt;br/&gt;
&lt;a href=&quot;file:/Users/ryan/, file:/Users/ryan/Users&quot; class=&quot;external-link&quot; target=&quot;_blank&quot; rel=&quot;nofollow noopener&quot;&gt;file:/Users/ryan/, file:/Users/ryan/Users&lt;/a&gt;&lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;This is problematic if the script was run from the root directory since the URLs will be scanned the directories recursively. Ultimately leading to a situation where the entire FileSystem is scanned. This has been known to cause issues for some Docker installations. &lt;/p&gt;

&lt;p&gt;Typically this is worked around by editing the the kafka-run-class script however I think we should handle this within Connect itself by excluding the root directory. &lt;/p&gt;


